[3] South Carolina man bitten by rabid raccoon
Date: 9 Jul 2010
Source: WLTX.com [edited]
<http://www.wltx.com/news/story.aspx?storyid=89710&catid=2>


After a Rock Hill man was exposed to rabies, health professionals at
DHEC are urging pet owners make sure that their animals are
vaccinated against the disease.

In a news release from the Department of Health and Environmental
Control (DHEC), officials said the man was exposed to rabies when he
was attacked by a raccoon as he tried to remove it from a trap. Sue
Ferguson with DHEC's Bureau of Environmental Health said that the man
is receiving preventive inoculations, because the disease is fatal to
humans and animals once it reaches the brain.

"Anyone bitten, scratched or otherwise exposed to the saliva of a
rabid animal must undergo immediate measures to stop the virus from
reaching the brain," Ferguson said. She said for residents to "avoid
wild animals acting tame and tame animals acting wild."

Ferguson said that each year, about 400 Palmetto State residents are
required to have preventive treatment for rabies. Most exposures come
from being bitten or scratched by a rabid animal, she says.
Typically, wild animals carry the disease, but domesticated animals
can still contract it.

"Residents should make sure their pets are regularly vaccinated
against the disease. State law requires that all pets be vaccinated
against rabies," Ferguson said.

--
