[6] Family in Nebraska exposed to rabid skunk
Date: 10 Jul 2010
Source: The Lincoln Journal Star [edited]
<http://journalstar.com/news/local/article_25b39d28-8c80-11df-ac77-001cc4c03286.html>


A domestic cat contracted rabies while defending kittens from a
skunk, forcing a Saline County family of 3 to get precautionary
immunization shots.

The skunk attacked the mother cat, and saliva was probably exchanged
or got into an open wound, according to health officials. Tuesday [6
Jul 2010], the cat started exhibiting neurological symptoms
associated with rabies, including sleepiness, fever, lack of
coordination and aggressiveness. Jane Ford of the district health
department said the kittens will be put to sleep because they are
likely infected with rabies.

There have been 31 animal cases of rabies in Nebraska so far this
year [2010], but that number may rise, according to health officials.

Animals looking to re-establish or aggressively defend their
territory after flood waters recede may contract the deadly but
preventable disease from other animals during fights. So far, most
cases are in skunks, but rabies has also infected a cow, bat and a
few dogs in the state.

--
