[9] North Carolina rabid fox
Date: 14 Jul 2010
Source: Salisbury Post [edited]
<http://www.salisburypost.com/News/071410-ninth-rowan-rabies-case-qcd>


A Gold Hill woman's dog was to be euthanized after killing a rabid
fox this week, Rowan County Animal Control said.

The incident marks Rowan County's 9th rabies case of the year [2010].

Angela Fesperman, of Old U.S. 80, reported that her dog, a male lab
mix named Jake, had killed a baby fox. The dog was not current on its
rabies shots and was placed in quarantine at the Rowan County Animal
Shelter while the fox was tested for rabies.

Animal Control learned Tuesday [6 Jul 2010] the fox had tested
positive for rabies. The dog was to be euthanized at the owner's
request, Animal Control said.

This marks the 3rd rabies case involving a fox this year [2010],
according to Animal Control. Four of the cases involved raccoons, and
2 involved skunks.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>

[Each state has its own rabies regulations. However, it is general
practice that any unvaccinated animal encountering a rabid animal
will be euthanized, as the unvaccinated pet represents a potential
exposure to rabies to the owner. This loss of life can be prevented
by vaccination against rabies.

These reports emphasize that urban as well as rural animals are at
risk of encountering a rabid animal.

People who are bitten or scratched need to seek immediate medical
care for treatment of the injury and for post exposure prophylaxis
against rabies. - Mod.TG]
